  "prompt": "How long can a milkshake last out of the fridge?",
  "response": "A milkshake that contains dairy products, such as milk and ice cream, is considered a perishable food item. To ensure both safety and optimal quality, it's important to adhere to the following guidelines:\n\n1. **Time at Room Temperature:**\n   - **Standard Room Temperature (68\u201372\u00b0F or 20\u201322\u00b0C):** Do not leave a milkshake out of the fridge for more than **2 hours**.\n   - **Hot Environments (Above 90\u00b0F or 32\u00b0C):** Reduce this time to **1 hour** to prevent the growth of harmful bacteria.\n\n2. **Quality Considerations:**\n   - Even within the safe time frames, a milkshake may begin to lose its desired consistency and flavor. Ingredients can separate, and the texture may become less creamy and more watery.\n\n3. **Storage Tips:**\n   - **Refrigeration:** If you need to store a milkshake after preparation, place it in the refrigerator as soon as possible. Store it in an airtight container to maintain freshness.\n   - **Consumption Window:** For the best taste and safety, consume refrigerated milkshakes within **1\u20132 days**. Shake or stir it well before drinking, as separation may occur during storage.\n\n4. **Signs of Spoilage:**\n   - **Off Smell:** A sour or unusual odor indicates that the milkshake has likely spoiled.\n   - **Change in Texture:** Excessive separation or the presence of lumps can be signs of spoilage.\n   - **Unpleasant Taste:** If the milkshake tastes off, it's best to discard it.\n\n5. **Special Considerations:**\n   - **Homemade vs. Commercial:** Homemade milkshakes might lack preservatives found in commercial products, potentially shortening their safe consumption window.\n   - **Ingredients:** Adding perishable ingredients like fresh fruit or certain flavorings may also affect how long the milkshake remains safe and tasty.\n\n**Safety First:** When in doubt, it's better to err on the side of caution. Consuming spoiled dairy products can lead to foodborne illnesses, which may cause symptoms like stomach cramps, nausea, vomiting, or diarrhea.\n\n**Summary:**\n- **Maximum Time Out of Fridge:** 2 hours at room temperature; 1 hour in hot conditions.\n- **Refrigerated Storage:** Consume within 1\u20132 days for best quality and safety.\n\nBy following these guidelines, you can enjoy your milkshake safely while maintaining its delicious taste and creamy texture.",
